<br>
What's important here?<br>
In my opinion its to have as many people as possible get to experiance as much of the game as possible.  <br>
<br>
The trade system sucks enough as it is.  It rewards people who get their first, then by the time that the people who can eventually get there, but are two or three steps behind, that item is utterly worthless.  So, you have the never ending cycle of 'the rich get richer, the poor get poorer'... is this representative of real life? yes, is it fun? not if you are on the short end of the stick.<br>
<br>
It'd be great if there was a way for things to better hold their initial value, or perhaps it'd be great if there was a way to 'cap' the price on a particular item so that it never really depreciates.  Item X is worth Y pp, and that's that, perhaps have some sort of predefined amortization schedule?  I dunno, maybe initially an item is worth 1.2 x W, then as the world starts becoming saturated with the item is worth X, then as another expansion comes out, and the item starts becoming obsolete, it stabalizes at 0.7 x X.  Perhaps a players CHA could be used to affect this price? I dunno, I see alot of creative ways to implement this kind of controlled communistic approach to it.  Obviously numbers could be adjusted, but, it would keep items from becoming trash and would help control inflation as well.  That's the problem with muds - inflation.  Currently there is no known way to prevent it.  There are no interest rates to adjust, or trade tariffs to modify.  Shit just gets farmed until its completely valuless, like a used up coal mine - dig as fast as you can till its gone, then move on and wreck the next piece of land.  Rinse and repeat.<br>
<br>
I dunno. Obviously the people who got there first, and then continue to get there first would utterly hate this idea.  But, people who can't play full time, would not be as 'penalized' as they currently are.<br>
<br>
comments?<br>
